### Description

If we pass the property whose type contains only falsy types to the `*ngIf` directive:

```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: `
    <p *ngIf="falsy as f">
      <!-- no compilation errors -->
      <app-child [str]="f"></app-child>
      <app-child [str]="falsy"></app-child>
    </p>
  `,
  standalone: true,
  imports: [CommonModule, ChildComponent],
})
export class AppComponent {
  falsy: false | null | undefined = false;
}

@Component({
  selector: 'app-child',
  template: '{{ str }}',
  standalone: true,
})
export class ChildComponent {
  @Input() str = '';
}
```

the type of the passed property, as well as its alias, will be `any` within the `*ngIf` template.

Based on the context type guard:

```ts
static ngTemplateContextGuard<T>(
  dir: NgIf<T>, ctx: any
): ctx is NgIfContext<Exclude<T, false | 0 | '' | null | undefined>> {
  return true;
}
```

I expected the type to be `never`.

